external_knowledge:
- "Epics" refers to films with a runtime of more than 120 minutes;
- "Cinematic maestro" refers to the director of the film;
- "Average income" refers to the average revenue generated by the films.

- "Top three directors" refers to directors ranked 1, 2, or 3 within their genre;
- "Average revenue" is calculated by averaging the revenue of all films directed by a director within a specific genre;
- "Genres they excel in" refers to the genres where the directors have the highest average revenue.

- Revenue is converted from a string format (with dollar signs and commas) to a real number for accurate aggregation;
- The average rating is calculated using the IMDB rating of the films;
- The top film is selected based on a combination of the highest average rating and total revenue.

- "Top 10 films" refers to the highest-ranked films based on IMDB ratings within each genre;
- "Shine brightest" is a metaphor for having the highest IMDB ratings;
- "Sea of critics" refers to the large number of voters (more than 1000) who have rated the films.

- 'Highest rated film' refers to the film with the highest average rating;
- In case of a tie in average rating, the film with the highest total revenue is considered higher ranked;
- The rank is determined by the order of average rating and total revenue.

- "shine the brightest" refers to having the highest average rating;
- "top three" refers to the films with the highest average ratings within each genre;
- "pinnacle of their genre" refers to the films with the highest average rating among the top 3 in their respective genres.

- "pinnacle of both audience acclaim and box office success" refers to films that are ranked first in both average user ratings and revenue generated;
- "average user ratings" are calculated by averaging the ratings given by users for each film;
- "revenue generated" is the total box office earnings for each film.

- Meta score is a standardized score out of 100 that reflects the overall quality of a film based on critical reviews;
- Revenue is the total income generated by a film, typically from box office sales and other distribution channels;
- The average rating of a film is calculated based on user reviews, typically on a scale of 1 to 5.

- "Top 10 genres" refers to the genres with the highest average IMDB ratings;
- "Metaphorically speaking" implies using figurative language to describe the genres;
- "Most celebrated and acclaimed types of stories" refers to genres that are highly rated on IMDB;
- "Film industry" refers to the context of movies and their ratings and revenues.

- "crowning jewels" refers to the top-rated films in each genre;
- "highest average IMDB rating" is a measure of the film's critical reception;
- "most votes" indicates the film's popularity among viewers.

- "The turn of the millennium to the dawn of the new decade" refers to the years 2000 to 2020;
- "Captivated the hearts of more than a thousand voters" implies the films have more than 1000 votes;
- "Stellar average rating above 4" means the average rating is greater than 4;
- "Financial spoils" refers to the revenue generated by the films;
- "Visionary directors" refers to the directors of the films.
